section.p:
A real number like 3.1459, which can be written with a finite number of digits, is shorthand for a sum of rational numbers:

        3.1459 \amp= \underbrace{3}_{\text{integer part}} 
          + \underbrace{\frac{1}{10}}_{\text{tenths}} 
          + \underbrace{\frac{4}{100}}_{\text{hundreths}} 
          + \underbrace{\frac{5}{1000}}_{\text{thousandths}} 
          + \underbrace{\frac{9}{10000}}_{\text{ten thousandths}}
        \amp= 3 + \frac{1459}{10000} =  \frac{31459}{10000}.

    In fact, every rational number has a decimal representation provided we allow the digits to eventually repeat a regular pattern infinitely often. We write a bar over the digits that repeat.

statement.p:
The following examples provide decimal representations of some rational numbers.
        \frac{1}{2} = 0.5000\ldots = 0.5\overline{0} = 0.5
        \frac{2}{3} = 0.6666\ldots = 0.\overline{6}
        \frac{12}{37} = 0.324\,324\,324\ldots = 0.\overline{324}
        \frac{381}{148} = 2.57\,432\,432\,432\ldots = 2.57\overline{432}

 Work from left to right evaluating the expression respecting the following order:


Parentheses: Perform all calculations inside parentheses or brackets (if parentheses are nested, work from inside out);

Exponents: Evaluate all exponential expressions a^b;

Multiplication and Division: Evaluate all products and quotients;

Addition and Subtraction: Evaluate all sums and differences.

section.p:
If a is non-zero (see
) real number, then 1/a is called its reciprocal. Multiplying a by its reciprocal results in one:
a \times \frac{1}{a} = 1. It is for this reason that 1/a is sometimes called the multiplicative inverse of a. For instance, 2 is the multiplicative inverse of 1/2 because 2\times (1/2) = 1.

solution.p:
The sum of the portions should add to one, so that the missing fraction is

  1-\frac{1}{3}-\frac{2}{5} \amp= \frac{15}{15} - \frac{5}{15} - \frac{6}{15} 
  \amp= \frac{15-5-6}{15} 
    \amp= \frac{4}{15}

statement.p:
Evaluate completely



              \displaystyle\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2


              \displaystyle\frac{2^2}{3}



              \displaystyle\frac{-2^2}{3}



              \displaystyle\frac{(-2)^2}{3}



              \displaystyle\left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)^2



              \displaystyle\left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)^3

solution.p:
Remember that exponents are considered before multiplication or division in PEMDAS.



              \displaystyle\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2 = \frac{2^2}{3^2} = \frac{4}{9}


              \displaystyle\frac{2^2}{3} = \frac{4}{3}



              \displaystyle\frac{-2^2}{3} = -\frac{4}{3}



              \displaystyle\frac{(-2)^2}{3} = \frac{4}{3}



              \displaystyle\left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)^2 = \left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)\cdot\left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)
        = \frac{4}{9}



              \displaystyle\left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)^3 = \left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)\cdot\left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)\cdot\left(-\frac{2}{3}\right) = - \frac{8}{27}

section.p:
The absolute value |x| of a real number x provides its 
magnitude, i.e. how large it is without regard to being positive or negative. Geometrically, it represents the distance the number is from zero along the real number line. 

  Image of the real number line and the absolute value of a number depicting distance from zero.We can express this precisely with the conditional expression
|x| = \begin{cases} 
  x, \quad &\text{if $x \geq 0$}\\
  -x, \quad & \text{if $x \lt 0$}
\end{cases}For example, 
|4|=4, \quad \text{because $4 \geq 0$},
while the absolute value of -4 is the opposite of -4:
|-4| = -(-4) = 4, \quad \text{because $4 \lt 0$.}
Note that |0| = 0. Formulas like Equation 
which involving multiple cases are common in engineering. Take some time to carefully understand the notation used above.
